🪜 1. Initialize Git in your project folder
git init


This starts a new Git repository inside your project.

🧾 2. Add all files to Git tracking
git add .


Adds all files in your folder to be tracked by Git.

🧍 3. Commit your changes
git commit -m "Initial commit"


Saves your added files with a message describing the change.

🌐 4. Create a new repository on GitHub

Go to https://github.com/new

Give it a name (example: my-project)

Choose Public (so everyone can see it)

Don’t add README (since you already have one locally)

🔗 5. Connect your local repo to GitHub

Copy the repo URL (HTTPS format), then run:

git remote add origin https://github.com/USERNAME/REPO_NAME.git


Example:

git remote add origin https://github.com/nzm-777/my-project.git

🚀 6. Push your project to GitHub
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main


This pushes your code to the GitHub main branch.

🧭 7. (Later) When you make changes:
git add .
git commit -m "Updated feature"
git push

🧹 8. Check status and logs
git status
git log

🪣 9. Clone any repository (if you want to download others’ projects)
git clone https://github.com/USERNAME/REPO_NAME.git

✅ Summary of All Commands
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/USERNAME/REPO_NAME.git
git push -u origin main
